stagram.com&amp;_nc_gid=kC0vaN9UlwrFdT9uYnaoJw&amp;_nc_ss=7a338&amp;oh=00_AfzEMYq34A1q9cskY203gkUEbAWI51ewbHSU_5esVPy2Hw&amp;oe=69CA2865" alt="Slide 3 fra @drmichelledavenport" style="max-width: 48%; margin: 0 1% 8px 0;" /><img src="https://scontent-cph2-1.cdninstagram.com/v/t51.82787-15/591181528_18340862443233412_8966630779709715171_n.jpg?stp=dst-jpg_e15_s480x480_tt6&amp;_nc_cat=104&amp;ig_cache_key=Mzc4NzAxMDAxMzQyNTQ5NTQyNw%3D%3D.3-ccb7-5&amp;ccb=7-5&amp;_nc_sid=58cdad&amp;efg=eyJ2ZW5jb2RlX3RhZyI6InhwaWRzLjcyMHg5NjAuc2RyLkMzIn0%3D&amp;_nc_ohc=0bl8LsDY3yoQ7kNvwHM0RVY&amp;_nc_oc=AdrAflzrrHxi1owxvDRholRulmCxk1bWPQkOcdt4Ax2MgZTENMWw4eqqM4IMJjG9vrc&amp;_nc_ad=z-m&amp;_nc_cid=0&amp;_nc_zt=23&amp;_nc_ht=scontent-cph2-1.cdninstagram.com&amp;_nc_gid=kC0vaN9UlwrFdT9uYnaoJw&amp;_nc_ss=7a338&amp;oh=00_AfwmX261g9JHqW6Icl5FJL-XlV5fETixJgAdqfgaWIDg_A&amp;oe=69CA15DD" alt="Slide 4 fra @drmichelledavenport" style="max-width: 48%; margin: 0 1% 8px 0;" /></p><p><strong>🖼️ Slideshow (6 medier)</strong></p><p><strong>@drmichelledavenport</strong></p><p>My Favorite Cookware for Water-Based Cooking<br/>
<br/>
The cookware you use might matter more than you think, and not for the reasons most cooking sites tell you, but because cooking the wrong way can actively work against your health. <br/>
<br/>
If you’ve been here before you already know I’m all about water-based cooking, which based on countless clinical studies and research, is the best way to slow aging in the kitchen. Water-based cooking minimizes the formation of advanced glycation end products (AGEs) and other inflammatory compounds that form when we cook with high heat and oil. <br/>
<br/>
The how is something I demonstrate in my videos, but the question I get most often isn’t about technique, but cookware. <br/>
<br/>
Over the years, I’ve received countless questions about the cookware that appears in my videos—where to buy it, what to prioritize, whether specific pieces are necessary. The truth is, I collect (ahem, hoard) beautiful cookware and serveware. Many pieces come from travels or are sentimental objects handed down to me. The wooden bowls you often see, for example, were made by my father-in-law. I have a ceramic tea set my late grandfather handed down to me. But you don’t need any of these specific items to cook this way.<br/>
<br/>
My favorite non/toxic pieces are: <br/>
<br/>
Clay pots (donabes, tagines, dulsots, etc)<br/>
Stainless steel pots<br/>
Steamers and steamer inserts <br/>
Cast iron<br/>
A select number of appliances like induction pots and instant pots <br/>
<br/>
For a breakdown of all these different pieces in further detail you can check out my Substack ❤️ if you want to see specific examples you can see them in my Amazon store in my link in bio too.<br/>
<br/>
Xo<br/>
Dr. Michelle <br/>
.<br/>
.<br/>
.<br/>
.<br/>
.<br/>
.<br/>
#longevity #glycation #waterbasedcooking</p><p><a href="https://www.instagram.com/p/DSOLL_YEs8N/">Se slideshow på Instagram</a></p>]]></description>
