      <title>The key to health and longevity is living like you’re human. Last week I stumble...</title>
      <link>https://www.instagram.com/p/DSGJf1bEvK0/</link>
      <description><![CDATA[<p><a href="https://www.instagram.com/p/DSGJf1bEvK0/"><img src="https://scontent-cph2-1.cdninstagram.com/v/t51.82787-15/591161042_18340525270233412_376581669808674498_n.jpg?stp=dst-jpg_e15_s640x640_tt6&amp;_nc_cat=105&amp;ig_cache_key=Mzc4NDc1NDMwNjkzNjQwMjYxMjE4MzQwNTI1MjY0MjMzNDEy.3-ccb7-5&amp;ccb=7-5&amp;_nc_sid=58cdad&amp;efg=eyJ2ZW5jb2RlX3RhZyI6InhwaWRzLjEwODB4MTkyMC5zZHIuQzMifQ%3D%3D&amp;_nc_ohc=K2yb0X6SpuoQ7kNvwGvRd75&amp;_nc_oc=AdrAc-BcGgdbe1FQENNsOqRtY-mRGZH6uQ7RqAe9ZAJXF5HW4Jjwb-e1cYyfJwrMGG8&amp;_nc_ad=z-m&amp;_nc_cid=0&amp;_nc_zt=23&amp;_nc_ht=scontent-cph2-1.cdninstagram.com&amp;_nc_gid=kC0vaN9UlwrFdT9uYnaoJw&amp;_nc_ss=7a338&amp;oh=00_AfyYH6ZWuhMJniG9Q7gYOavsfiwAVX6qHbNXGgF2GGYqqg&amp;oe=69CA310C" alt="Video-thumbnail fra @drmichelledavenport" /></a></p><p><strong>🎬 Video</strong></p><p><strong>@drmichelledavenport</strong></p><p>The key to health and longevity is living like you’re human. <br/>
<br/>
Last week I stumbled upon a video of this adorable old monk who was sharing ancient health tips. He had millions of followers but something looked off so I did some digging and that’s when I realized damn, I just got fooled by AI.<br/>
<br/>
I felt so upset. Like what do you mean we are already in dystopia?? <br/>
<br/>
What does this mean for trust, the distribution of knowledge and human faces? <br/>
<br/>
But then I calmed down and thought … an AI will never be able to share old family recipes. Or be able to show you the imperfect beauty of hand made cabbage rolls, the first dish I learned from my mom. Or reassure you by saying hey, I did my PhD only to learn that grandma was right.<br/>
<br/>
Because the most human thing about our food has nothing to do with the food, you know? It’s about us.<br/>
<br/>
Anyway these are cabbage rolls I made with my hands. For you to view because I care about you and your health. It’s the first dish I ever learned 20 years ago as a college student and I still love them today (thanks, Mom)! <br/>
<br/>
Slow aging because they’re steamed, which you probably already know if you’ve been here!<br/>
<br/>
Ingredients <br/>
1.5 lbs ground pork, chicken or broken firm tofu <br/>
A knob of ginger, grated <br/>
1 large clove of garlic, grated <br/>
1 shallot, diced finely<br/>
Splash of mirin wine<br/>
Heavy sprinkle of salt <br/>
Ground pepper if you like it <br/>
Prettiest Napa cabbage you can find, medium size<br/>
Either long chives or scallions<br/>
<br/>
Directions<br/>
1. Wash then either steam (1-2 min) or microwave (2 min) the cabbage leaves until they are soft. <br/>
2. Mix the ground pork (or chicken, or tofu, whatever you are using) with the Mirin wine, salt, shallot, garlic, and ginger.<br/>
3. Place about one tablespoon of the mixture on the leaf and roll up to the stem.<br/>
4. Wrap with chives or scallions. If you are using scallions, I recommend also steaming or microwaving them so they soften.<br/>
5. Steam the rolls until the inside is cooked through, about 10-12 minutes on medium-high heat.<br/>
6. Serve with rice or on anything else you want ❤️<br/>
<br/>
Enjoy!<br/>
Xo<br/>
Dr. Michelle<br/>
.<br/>
.<br/>
.<br/>
.<br/>
.<br/>
.<br/>
.<br/>
